  "text": "Dogs (normal, nϭ4; CHF, nϭ6) were anesthetized with intravenous sodium thiopental (30 mg/kg) followed by ␣-chloralose (10 mg/kg) and were intubated. A median sternotomy was made, and sections of the right and left ventricular apices were removed and washed in a nominally Ca 2ϩ -free Tyrode's solution gassed with 100% O 2 . Right and left ventricular sections were divided into Ϸ1-mm 2 pieces with a scalpel and then dispersed separately using an albumin-containing collagenase-pronase solution described previously. [CITATION_1] 40 The tissue was placed in enzyme-containing flasks in a shaker bath and agitated for 10 minutes at 37°C. After filtration through a 250-m nylon mesh to remove incompletely digested material, cells were washed twice and stored in a modified Kraft-Brühe solution containing (mmol/L) KOH 132, glutamic acid 120, KCl 2.5, KH 2 PO 4 10, MgSO 4 1.8, K 2 EGTA 0.5, glucose 11, taurine 10, and HEPES 10 (pH 7.2, 295 mOsm/L). Typical yields were 30% to 50% Ca 2ϩ -tolerant rod-shaped cells. Myocytes were used within 6 hours of harvesting, and only quiescent cells with regular striations and no evidence of membrane blebbing were selected for study. Only quiescent cells were chosen to eliminate myocytes that might have been damaged in isolation. This procedure may eliminate CHF cells that were most severely injured in vivo from the study because it excludes cells that become spontaneously active in vivo, and cells severely injured in vivo may not survive isolation.",
